Ambassador to the EU Vicenova:
The Czechs have a reputation as adversaries and skeptics of the euro.
“The Lisbon Treaty has caused significant differences between individual organizations.”
“I didn’t expect such a cruel war.”
“It will take five or six years before the situation stabilizes, calms down and all players get used to their new roles,” EU Ambassador Milena Vicenova said.
She proved how much she adhered to her motto "Clear and Open about Europe" in the first part of her lecture, where she described the individual EU institutions and the relationship between them so simply and clearly that many lecturers from the Faculty of Law of the KU would be envious.
Moreover, Vicenova praised the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
“At first, critics said he was an ordinary gray office mouse that couldn’t perform any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he handled his role.”
“He is a person who can listen to the twenty-seven participating countries at the same time, communicate well with them and who has a clear idea of which way the EU should develop.”
She explained her new position as a representative for international relations and security issues in response to the question: "Who is the European Union? What number should I call?"; i.e. as an important step towards unification and greater transparency of the Union's policy towards countries such as China or India.
No one is going to ban our cheeses.
Vicenova further focused on a program that was key to the EU in the past, present and near future.
She called the Czech Republic's presidency a success in the year before last.
The Czechs were dealing with an impending financial crisis; they overcame the crisis and organized the Eastern Partnership Summit.
She said that the resignation of the government at that time was a negative phenomenon that caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
Currently, the Czech Republic is very busy in the EU.
As the Ambassador said, both the presidency and the subsequent financial crisis have caused the ongoing fermentation.
In addition, it is necessary to adopt a new seven-year EU budget, which is very difficult, given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be scarce and economical, which areas will be preferred; which countries will receive more support and which less; all these issues are in the upcoming program.
The Ambassador recalled the key slogans that she brought to Brussels: “About Europe, in an understandable language”.
“I really don’t like abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that no one understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curved or round cucumbers, bananas of all sizes, or that someone is going to ban our varieties of cheese.
It is also going to use the EU environment more effectively and attract more Czechs to European organizations.
A multi-speed Europe is our future
The Ambassador claims that the Czechs are considered Euro-skeptics; as well as people who note the negative rather than the positive side of things.
She wants more representatives of the Czech Republic to be involved in European organizations.
She believes that several factors are to blame: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivational letters; at the same time with little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful chairmanship of the Czech Republic, she noted the power and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland and Hungary, and a Slovak joins us, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, what's the meeting about, the Visegrad Group again?' and he's not happy about it.
In the future, Vicenov expects mainly new strict rules for the budgetary policy of the member states.
Compared to the new European Federation, she considers the idea of a two-speed, if not multi-speed, Europe more realistic.
“We have countries both inside and outside the eurozone.”
“We have the Schengen area, and we already have the institute of enhanced cooperation.”
“For the first time, it has been said that countries that want to unite, while those that don’t want to can stay away.”
"The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe," Vicenova expects.
In this regard, she stressed the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in advancing the rule that all issues affecting the whole EU should be discussed by all member states, not just the eurozone.
Brand history:
The innovator IBM is entering the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find the word that best expresses the IMB strategy, the closest one is likely to be “long-lasting.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The company’s longevity was laid down by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He believed in his motto that many of the world’s problems could be easily solved if people wanted to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began to publish in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means constantly moving towards the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, although it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, this has allowed us to transform technology, business and the company.
In the second century, we hope to achieve even more,” said Samuel J. Palmizano, the company’s current CEO, on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complicated system
