Dynamics of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed to operate in the former Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, travel agencies of the time mostly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, on vacation, Czech tourists went to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. Then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which entailed significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter was needed from that country; otherwise, individual travel was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered travel to the West, but you either had to stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or have “good friends” at the agency.
And that's not all.
A currency permit was necessary for travel to the West. It was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit it was impossible to obtain money (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most often, the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the emergence of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit persists to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While before 1989 vacations in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we no longer realize, is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular currently Croatia, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the very beginning of 1990, the need for a visa to the neighboring countries of Western Europe was abolished. This marked the beginning of a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of traveling to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at the time was insufficient for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism in that period was the desire to bring their own food (canned food, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech koruna. After decades, our tourists are finally free to buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income were rising, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights operated by charter airlines. Compared to the past, air travel has now become incredibly cheap thanks to the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all the developed countries of the world, except the United States. This made our travel even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000. Great demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have been delivering Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter, flights from the Czech Republic will depart to twelve exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished the requirement to obtain a visa for Czech tourists. Thus, our country has permanently joined the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than 15,000 crowns per person during vacation abroad, including their expenses at their destination.
