The Pavilion of Austria, designed by Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels, is a famous example of modern post-war architecture with its simple shapes, glass halls, bold that expressed faith in technical progress.
The Schwanzer pavilion won the Grand Prix of Architecture in 1958 for its light floating structure made of steel and glass.
The building is considered a landmark in modern architecture.
