Eventually, it became world-famous in 1973 for its legendary four-cylinder BMW tower and its sister, the bowl-shaped building.
The pavilion, conceived as a building for temporary exhibitions, was moved to the Swiss Garden near Vienna's South Railway Station, transformed and opened as a 20th-century museum in 1962 - and is often referred to as the "20th-century house" for this reason.
However, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - it had no walls on which to hang works of art, and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna received a new home.
The house has been empty since 2001, and its condition has been getting worse and worse.
Architect Adolf Kri<0xC5><0xA1>anitz has now restored the pavilion, which was called the "21st century house" and will be used as a museum of contemporary art.
This museum is a branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open the first exhibition on Tuesday evening - in all senses a joyful event.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, contributed to the new start.
Husslein-Arco, a graduate of the Faculty of Art History with a brilliant career as a skater in her youth, who worked at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Museum of Modernity in Salzburg, persuaded politicians and curators to continue the reconstruction, raised public funds and private donations and made a decision on how
The new museum was to accommodate the permanent exhibition of the Fritz Wotruba Foundation, a cafe and a bookstore along with contemporary art. An office building was also to be built.
Strict control & limited budget
Kri<0xC5><0xA1>anitz was then the ideal candidate for the project.
He was known, of course, for the restoration and expansion of the Vienna Secession by Josef Olbrich, and won the contest, but he also studied with Schwantz at the Vienna University of Technology, and the pavilion was for him an "exceptionally important place", where he attended exhibitions "almost every week".
He knew the original design and knew the challenges that stood in front of the building, a building that had already lost some of its grandeur and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and transformed.
The problems that arose during the last restructuring were much more serious. The building was a "energy absorber", says Krishanitz.
The window profiles on the glass facade were replaced, fiberglass-reinforced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced with high-strength safety glass.
The steel bars of the thermal bridge were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos was removed from the ceilings.
The two lower floors have created space for a new use of the building, the fallen light well between the building and the street provides lighting – a practically new building, but still an elegant Schwantzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors were preserved, and the building was painted in the old red-brown color of corrosion protection.
The cinema hall is the same as it used to be.
All this under strict control of the museum administration and with a limited budget.
