Peter Englund’s tense and very good new book, Beauty and Sorrow: A Personal History of the First World War, begins with a long list of actors from which the heart freezes.
Here’s a tip to read on: Carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund narrates, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon at the moments when, like one of these men and women, you stray from the road and get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he’s written now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as “a work on anti-history.”
There are few known names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, skilful journalists, or discussions of tactics and military equipment.
It’s not so much a book about what was, he explains, as “a book about what it was like.” It’s about “feelings, impressions, experiences and a state of mind.”
Beauty and Sorrow brings together the experiences of 20 more or less unremarkable men and women on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and nerd scientists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Someone will be taken prisoner, lose an arm or a leg, go crazy or die.
Their lives flicker here like church candles: new ones are added to a multitude of others, and some are extinguished at this time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is an amendment to the notion that World War I was only a heavy trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully gives a panorama of other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Beehives fall on the soldiers in this book; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unsolvable problem is the tsetse flies.
It's an exciting book, almost from the start.
War covers the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina, smelling of smokeless gunpowder.
When a cannonade is heard nearby, and you are a woman and you are at home with children, will you stay in place or run away?
Either way, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what is happening and in general why it is necessary to fight in this war.
“The lack of facts,” says Mr. Englund, “is replenished by conjectures, assumptions, hopes, fears, obsessions, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.”
