Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was an ordinary guy laying out his anti-immigration views online.
Breivik, who confessed to the July massacre in Norway that claimed the lives of 77 people, appeared for his first open court hearing on Monday.
Although Breivik could have acted alone, he was far from being alone online: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack at his computer, chatting with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, the researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It’s easy – you just have to go to Facebook.
“We realized that it was not difficult to approach them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European cyber-populism by the British DEMOS Research Centre.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so large, says Bartlett, that researchers could easily use the site’s advertising tool to single out the necessary demographics with scientific accuracy – which marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then pitched them an ad, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ad suggested the user undergo a survey that asked questions about their level of education, attitude to violence, and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without even leaving the office.
“This is a completely new way to conduct research,” says Bartlett.
Some results are not so striking: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young males dissatisfied with immigration.
But unexpectedly, “those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more intelligent, more democratic, and less aggressive than those who just hide behind a monitor.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends, which are expressed in 'Likes', posts on the wall and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook’s “super-update information” is triggering a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the site’s title in the headline by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it makes it possible to study people who cannot be approached on the street with a notebook.
“In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them.”
“You would have to join the party and they would never accept you,” says Bartlett.
“Facebook excludes all of this – you address them directly.”
Others say that with the help of this site it would be possible to identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunken exploits on Facebook were significantly more at risk for alcoholism than students who remained silent about it.
Moreno suggests that peers of students, such as their dorm mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who updates drunken status too often.
“You can’t solve the problem without identifying it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
“We have found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise have been found.”
Facebook also constantly retrieves all sorts of data about its users.
The site’s data processing team processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, midterm turnout in 2010, and the National Happiness Index (mostly using information that only they have access to – cyber-freedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection public for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become participants in a study they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined norms for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
“I don’t think many users even thought about what a researcher might be watching their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a study he conducted in 2006 using public student Facebook pages.
"As far as they could imagine, it was only between them and their friends."
This raises the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that the subject of the study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much information in the profile and on the user's page is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” says Selwyn.
That’s why, despite years of work in technology research, Selwyn thinks the notebook and pen are still the best research tools you can use.
