7 Lessons From Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview Showed at the Theatre This Week
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans may consider the biggest discovery in the newly uncovered interview, which was recalled ahead of the previews in major markets this week, is how much that creative mind understood in business processes and in manufacturing technology.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and a hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and modernizer of the production process, who believed that many business leaders suffered from “the sickness of thinking that a truly great idea is 90 percent work... [but] a great idea from a great product is separated by a huge amount of skilled labor.”
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created the television series Triumph of the Nerds about the advent of the personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a unique long conversation.
By that time, about 10 years had passed since Jobs was kicked out of Apple, and he was already fully working at his new computer company NeXT in anticipation of the mass development of the Internet.
While a small portion of Kringley's interviews were used in the Nerds, he says the original interviews disappeared during transportation.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which comes out in Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of detailed interviews, Jobs seems unusually prepared here to lay out his technology philosophy and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In four different moments during the interview, there are large intervals between questions and answers – 10-15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be more precise.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems annoyed by Kringley’s questions, forcing him to move more quickly to questions or phenomena of greater importance.
In the pre-Pixar, iPod, and iPhone era, Lost Interview has something sinisterly prophetic when Jobs evaluates what he sees companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of information technology.
It’s one thing to read about Jobs’ posthumous assessments of his work, but there’s something vulnerable and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, an anxious dreamer on the cusp of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Soon after he said everything here, he went and did it.
A brief summary of the seven significant findings of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All the time in business, I've been asking, 'Why do you do this?' And the answers you always get are, 'Oh, that's just how it's done.'
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks very deeply in business.
Here's what I learned.
Jobs continues to detail his efforts to streamline reporting at Apple.
Frustrated by the way expenses were recorded, often starting with “standard expenses” that were taken from the ceiling and then customized with “clarification,” he created an automated structure that ensured they could track business expenses down to the smallest detail.
Jokes about the Pope:
Jobs details the “blue box” he crafted with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device before, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the blue box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the box using an automatic phone, ordering a conversation and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until they connected as many stations as possible.
“We’ve covered the globe half a dozen times and you’ve been yelling at a vending machine phone, and it’s been penetrating a minute later into a neighboring vending machine phone,” Jobs says with a smile.
“We were young and all we learned was that we could make something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us knew a little bit, but we could craft the little thing that could control the big thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple could have ever come without it.
Jobs continues to describe in detail one famous trick that he and Wozniak practically coped with, calling the Vatican through a blue box at midnight and asking the Pope to call, struggling to copy Henry Kissinger.
When various members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to an American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the Pope himself was picked up to answer the phone.
On falling in love with technology (and the cold nickname of Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to assemble the frequency meter, he found Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a summer part-time job at Hewlett-Packard.
“It had a strong impact on me, it was the only company I saw at that age, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP's employees visiting the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the very first desktop computer".
It was the size of a suitcase, it had a small monitor with a beam tube, and I fell in love with it.
I often drove to HP as a teenager and swirled around that car and wrote programs for it.
About improvised innovation:
In several places, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
At the dawn of his career, when he went to sell a handful of circuit boards, one buyer asked him to assemble a whole computer.
Working only 30 days on credit, he had to think through both the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later at Apple, he recalls the difficulties he encountered while developing a computer mouse:
"I remember the fierce arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to collect a mouse that would cost $300], and I was fed up, and I went out and found a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we were able to assemble for $15, which was incredibly reliable.
For companies that are losing energy:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs accurately predicted how many industry leaders would go wrong in their vision and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make the best copier or printer, and what?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company does not become more successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are the types of people] who eventually come to the management of companies, and the people who make the product are pushed out of the decision-making platform.
The product genius that led to this monopolistic position is being supplanted by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products – the required skill.
That's what happened to Xerox...
Xerox could take over the entire information technology industry.
It could have been ten times bigger, it could have been Microsoft of the '90s...
They were defeated in victory.
Innovation as a Form of Art:
“A great idea is separated from a great product by a great amount of skillful labor...when you unwind a great idea, it changes and grows.”
You will learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises you need to make – some things you won’t be able to force to make electrons, glass, robots, or factories.
You need to keep 5,000 ideas in your head — these concepts — connecting them all together.
Ultimately, it all comes down to taste – it all comes down to trying to express yourself in the best that humans have ever produced, and later – trying to bring that into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We were always ashamed to steal great ideas.
Part of what made the Macintosh famous was that the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happened to be the best IT professionals in the world.
If it weren’t for information technology, they would be doing amazing things in other areas.
