Stories of fraud in school and college exams are commonplace.
There were times when teachers gave students answers to tests in order to have a good assessment of their performance.
Mentors who are supposed to teach the opposite send a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
In one day, research shows you can be lied to 10 to 200 times.
Now it is assumed that a significant part of this is a lie for salvation.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of dating each other.
Detecting lies or incriminating them is a necessary skill for everyone, both for personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room game like, say, charades, where you have to exclaim “Caught!”, the detection of lies is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lies have been debunked.
Liars look into your eyes.
They do not always stutter, stutter, blush, or fuss.
It is not necessary to conclude from this that liars are difficult to notice and difficult to expose.
An experienced whistleblower can get to the truth by observing the structure of allegations, facial expressions, question structure, and time characteristics.
I’ve spent several years researching scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of lying knowledge, and it’s clear that lying detection is a modern skill that’s easy to learn and that helps navigate in our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from the study that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie more about others, usually to protect someone’s feelings that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried ones (but the lies they tell are most often brazen).
We also know that if you are perceived as a deceiver, others will feel less guilty by deceiving you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your object.
This is called "definition of the initial state."
This helps to provide a starting point for evaluating changes further.
Observe the posture, laughter, voice characteristics of your object.
It is good for you to know if a person is constantly tapping with his feet in a normal state, then you will not make unjust accusations when you see a tapping with his feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and nonverbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Deceivers can fix their upper body when trying to remember their story, they can put their feet towards the door, lean towards the exit, change their posture in a certain way, or demonstrate “relief after an interview” – that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture when all the difficult issues are behind.
Investigators often falsify the signal to end the interrogation just to see that relief after the interview.
So, pay attention to the speech of your object.
It is known that Scott Peterson stumbled and used the past time, claiming that his murdered wife was alive, which led to her searches throughout the country.
Vaccinating people can also use distancing in speech: “I didn’t have a sexual relationship with this woman ... Miss Lewinsky” or repeat the complex question altogether.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely noticeable.
Someone can use the “qualifying language” when answering the complex question: “Well ... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... as far as I know.”
This makes the answer more emotional than actual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magical means to detect a lie, but it is possible to master the skill of detecting deception.
These skills will increase the chances of everyone not to become a victim of skilled crooks in professional and personal life.
