Climate change has slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario López's reign in Sinaloa, unemployment and the illegal labor market increased, foreign funding declined, and the economy was weakened.
2011 is a year that will go down in the economic history of Sinaloa as related to the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés, also called the year of change, which gave rise to high hopes for economic development, but given the unfavorable climatic conditions of the beginning of the year, there was no growth, however, a decline in the main indicators of economic development was recorded.
The low temperatures of February not only led to millions of losses for the agricultural sector, but they limited the growth opportunities of the state economy, causing a decline in economic activity overall by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly due to a historical decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamics of other sectors of the economy.
According to the report on frost-affected areas provided by the Council for Sustainable Rural Development of Mexico, 835,582 hectares were affected, of which 78.03 per cent were completely affected and the remaining 21.07 per cent were partially affected. The main crops damaged were vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity caused, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state with more than half of the population, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, during the first three quarters there was an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate, from January to March 55,053 people were unemployed, with a share of 4.53% of the economically active population, in the second quarter of July 18.
Reduced liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is plagued by many factors, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly by actions that have been taken in public policy.
“What we’re seeing now is an increase in unemployment, which is due to several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market to limit the resources imposed by a law passed in Congress to fight money laundering, as people who illegally own dollars are not easy to work with, invest in and use in something,” he said.
Stopped Immigration
López Cervantes said that there is also a demographic factor in the increase in unemployment.
“The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad was limited in the United States, primarily because of difficulties with entry, and in the second - because once they enter, they already face many difficulties in finding work, so that a group of people stay and demand jobs here in the state, as a result, the unemployment rate is growing,” he said.
Violation of formal requirements
The analysis of Sinaloa’s labor market becomes worse if you pay attention to the large number of violations that prevail in working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the state’s active population works without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and irregularities in design, another reminder of work in the state is represented by low wages; the state has the lowest wages in the country, according to records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Ministry of Labor and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was up to September 5,352 pesos, well below the national average, which is 7,375 pesos.
Reduction of FDI
In addition to a decline in economic activity and a high unemployment rate, 2011 saw the largest outflow of foreign direct investment over the past 10 years, according to the Treasury Department, the state’s FDI was $630.697 from January to July, showing a drop of 87.74 percent compared to $5,143,312 over the same period last year.
For its part, the State Department of Economic Development recorded a total of 17,280,000 pesos of investment during the year, mostly in service companies.
Debt
Against the backdrop of the economic downturn, the state government requested in July during the state congress approval of a 3 billion peso loan that would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2,600 million pesos were approved at the local level, and no debt benefits were expected in any sector of the state economy until November.
Reactions
For business representatives, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés demonstrates a lack of government capabilities.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that during 2011 there was a lack of agreement on the wishes of various sectors, including the state government itself.
“The economic performance in Sinaloa this year was really low, we have to work hard to recover the positions lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we have not been able to coordinate the efforts of everyone and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better,” he said.
Economic slowdown
López Loredo said events such as early frosts this year halted the state’s economy and its efficiency and growth were limited.
"The low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy that is not getting fast enough to create economic dynamics that allows us to have an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and, therefore, at the end of the year, we close it below our expectations," he said.
Revision of direction
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, said the state needs to continue its most dynamic production activity.
“In general, we found that we were working on this, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, it is necessary to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
Upcoming work
President Coparmex stressed the importance of defining the future direction in order to better guide the government’s efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government is trying to be successful in various areas, in terms of economic development there is little progress, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He noted that the current administration has demonstrated progress in its own manner of conducting public policy.
“There are facts that allow us to say that the government is starting to get involved, and that I can say that some work has been done, and I think the government is aware that there is a lot more to be done,” he said.
