The court will approve the “transition to digital television” in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court has rejected constitutional claims put forward by the Senate and House of Representatives against a presidential decree that postpones the so-called “digital television transition” from 2021 to 2015 because the eight votes needed to overturn it were not obtained.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers, issuing a decree detailing the actions to move to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected because of the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes necessary for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television program is a right enshrined by law in the Federal Telecommunication Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Salvador, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the House of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the demand of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the prime minister said he disagreed with the draft arguments in the sense that the federal executive cannot determine by general rules the measures for which the state administration should prepare.
"I also do not believe that if this happened, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that the planning of state policy in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the management of the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals – one of the most important changes that has taken place in recent years – has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Delaying the transition, he said, would mean deferring the benefits of digital transformation, which involves meeting societal needs that have more than just a technical dimension, “as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he said, "require the work of the entire system, formed on the principle of state economic management, includes a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into the state executive power."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and did so with the help of the executive branch, despite the presence of highly specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be inferred from this that the Government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws passed by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
In Michoacán analyzes the possibility of counting "voice by voice"
According to the data transmitted to the PPRV, the difference between first and second place in the governorial elections is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes, accounting for 879 of the total number of 6.074 protocols.
The possibility of counting “vote by vote” is real with regard to this year’s election process in Michoacán, where, according to data obtained from the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governor’s elections is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes, which account for 879 of the total of 6,074 protocols.
In light of this, the Chairman of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (MII), Maria de Los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the Electoral Corps approved a set of principles to align local rules with federal electoral reform.
As it should be recalled, Michoacán did not pass the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Electoral Law, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the deadlines set forth in the law.
On the same day, November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice (SJJ) ruled on the constitutional claim put forward by the local legislature and called the vote of the state's constitutional reform representative "invalid and illegal", as he did not have the right to "allow or support them".
In an interview about the possibility of a “vote for a vote”, María de los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal argued that with the adoption of appropriate principles by the General Council, it would be possible to submit a partial or full vote count by a local electoral body.
Thus, a partial recalculation of one or more ballot boxes may be made under the condition that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no protocol for voting and counting documents in the ballot box or it is not in the possession of the chairman; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the minutes.
In addition, a general recount of votes in all ballot boxes may take place when there is a sign that the difference between the supposed candidate-winner of the elections under consideration and those who received the second place in the voting is less than or equal to one percent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from a representative of the party and/or coalition that put forward the second of the mentioned candidates.
A general recount of votes shall also be made if, at the end of the ordinary recount, it is established that the difference between the winner and the second-placed candidate is less than or equal to one percent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate has taken second place, in the event that the ballot boxes that were taken into account in the partial recount are excluded.
It is worth noting that in such a situation there are elections in Morelia, where, according to the PPRV, the difference between first and second places is only 0.16 percent, not even counting 129 votes out of the total number of 923 protocols.
