A new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to present a new government that will face a crisis that has put the country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italy's appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president on Wednesday to present a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take its positions.
Monty said he would present the president with the results of his negotiations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country’s ability to emerge from this difficult period,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that obstacles were overcome.
“The structure is now well outlined,” he said.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, which is much less than usual, as Italy struggled with a political and financial crisis that brought their debt to a critical level.
The administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
At the heart of the pressure on Monti to hurry, volatile markets set Italy’s BTP bond yield at more than 7% for 10 years, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to bail out.
Emma Marchegalia, leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told reporters after meeting Monti: “We said we would actively support this government.”
We believe that this government is Italy’s last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monti's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP's Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts should lead to a good outcome,” Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the technocratic government majority that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government should have strong parliamentary support for reforms that are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has stepped up pressure, warning that Monti’s failure could be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
He will finish his series of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief pause at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the value of Italy’s debt has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will be successful.
Rescuing Italy with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for modern eurozone financial defenders.
Monti said his government would exist until the next elections scheduled for 2013, despite widespread forecasts that politicians would only give him time to carry out reforms before calling new elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist it should be composed only of technical specialists, a testament to their dissatisfaction with the fact that the process is affected by the financial situation.
Political sources said the parties’ mutual mistrust and disagreement complicate the attempt to include political figures.
