The quintet included the country in the tour in honor of the twentieth anniversary of his career
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true.
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said that the band is ready to give one of the best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It’s been over 20 years of waiting, but the band says it’s also a dream come true for them to play in this country.
This was a statement by bassist and founder Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is in South America as part of a 20-year tour and will make its only stop in Central America on Sunday, 20th.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., along with the Los Angeles team The X and the local group Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from a conversation, the full transcript of which is available online at The Nation.
For your Costa Rican fans it is a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica? Do you know what your fans are experiencing?
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is only our second visit to South and Central America, and so far everything is going well.
I’ve only been to Costa Rica once – on vacation, it’s a beautiful country and I think we can stay there for a few days.
We are very happy to bring our music here.
I ask this because there is some commitment to the band; the fans live in tension in the days before the concert.
What would you say to your most loyal fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get here.
Some people, waiting for your concert, treat it like the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a little tension to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played in the last 21 years have taken place over the past two weeks.
We’ve had some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope it put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle, as far as these two things are concerned, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you learn about Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves here are incredible.
My friends always go surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua as well as Mexico, these are great places to surf, that’s how we learned about it, from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, you can say that you made a grand show with a lot of songs.
What do you plan to do in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there before, there’s no limit to what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible with a wide variety of songs; we will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a great variety of repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How do you do that?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs, and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven’t played in a while, it keeps us in tune and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and so I think it makes it more interesting for people.
This tour marks 20 years of career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe what you’ve done?
Yes, absolutely.
First, I think none of us could ever have imagined that we would be in a rock band and the fact that we have been doing this for over 20 years makes it look like a dream.
We are delighted with our success and we are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and love making music.
We are happy to go to places in the world where we have always wanted to go.
Everything is going very well for us.
What does it mean to you to be a significant part of the flowering of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great collectives.
We are good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s great when a movement grows out of a group of friends, and that’s unusual.
From time to time, one group from one city appears, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups appear at the same time in the same city.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle band.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden during their tour, so we are happy to be friends with all of them and it is an honor for us to be part of the Seattle sound that came out.
It is also very strange that a group like yours stays together and in the same composition for so long.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than many bands exist.
First, I think we’re lucky to still be alive, and second, we care about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to this, musical paths have also been opened that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other’s music and it couldn’t have been better.
Your attitude towards the word glory was not easy; but thanks to your success you were able to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became easier to find balance.
We take care not to be on tour for too long because it’s easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
