Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
The official delegation, led by Uruguay’s President José Mujica and composed of several ministers and businessmen, will arrive in Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and begin negotiations on the region’s political issues.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the most important point of an extensive plan of meetings with political, commercial authorities and meetings with the Uruguayan community living in Mexico, according to a schedule published by the Uruguayan leadership.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will be “favourable for the exchange of information on the issue of political relations between the two nations”, as the South American country’s leadership published on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderon’s support for Uruguay in an incident with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country in the list of tax havens at a G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that sparked Uruguay’s protest and recall for consultations of his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group formed from the most developed and developing countries, and has, in fact, had a tax information exchange agreement with the South American country since January this year to avoid double taxation.
The Government of Uruguay has tried in recent years to expedite the conclusion of tax exchange agreements in order to leave this “gray list” of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, compiled from countries that do not use international standards of tax cooperation.
As for the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in place since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
