MSS Announces Obesity Gene Search Program
Social Protection Leads Study on Obesity Gene Search in Children and Young Adults; Supported by IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young adults, dubbed the "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence" protocol, which will provide counting of signs associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the 21st Century National Medical Center, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been assembled.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (prescribed or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico City, where tests involving children will be conducted every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began to be conducted at the sports center in Cuauhtémoc (west of Mexico State), and from October 8, the events are held at the sports center in Nezahualcoyotl (east of Mexico State).
Once the goal of attracting 500 to 600 children is reached, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (South Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (North Mexico City).
He explained that the purpose of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, and the main goal is to gather three thousand children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 years with parental permission and under their supervision to fill out individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and a history of family inherited diseases to avoid the risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), measurements of blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) will be carried out on Saturday.
Cruz López said the study reflects health professionals’ concerns about the alarming weight gain among children.
In medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006, there was an increase in just 6 years: in the case of boys, 77 percent were obese, in the case of girls, 47%; in the case of overweight, there was also a significant increase," said the MSSI specialist.
He said the validity of the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from other peoples in their genetic history.
He reported that, on average, a Mexican is 65 percent descendant of American Indians, 30 percent descendant of Europeans, and five percent descendant of Africans, and this condition is reflected in genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, basically, the consequence of the genetics of obesity is the body’s inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories), and it is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit for participants is a comprehensive assessment of children, which can reveal whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, having dark folds on the neck (acants) and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with complete confidentiality, doctors pass it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV, and using transport for short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to the high calorie intake, that is, the increase in the consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Department of Chemistry, has developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the best quality, resistant to environmental and temperature influences.
If the signals sent by the road surface were paid attention, then it would be necessary to repair about 200 thousand pits for each rainy season in the metropolitan area in the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM Department of Chemistry, and adds that if the process of construction and maintenance of the paved road surface is correct.
In his lecture A Technological View of Pits, given as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nachera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and therefore counteract the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight called maltenes, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscous-elastic behavior.
The viscous behavior of bitumen lies in the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but varies throughout the day, depending on natural conditions and temperatures, said a specialist in chemical engineering.
The chemist noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which is composed of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the topmost layers is bitumen, composed of small stones lowered into bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is submerged in bitumen.
When moving vehicles and exerting effort, it helps the forces to distribute very well on the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be distributed even better, a chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt, he added, placed the last layer, which is called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, actually sand also submerged in the asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will contact the transport wheels, it should have more resistance than asphalt and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute these efforts, the wear layer also requires proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the condition of the asphalt.
When the earth is wet, water enters the coating and it is difficult for it to get out of it, this causes all layers of the coating to soften and, consequently, the formation of pits.
When the pits are formed, he said, the first wear layer is worn and only then it affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur instantly, this is a process that should be paid attention to at the first signs of ongoing repair programs.
Also, a member of the National System of Research explained that the transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each coating layer should always be associated with the transport load and it is necessary to ensure that this requirement is met in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of pits.
Rafael Herrera said that there is still a lot to learn about bitumen and make, for example, bitumen emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and even help to fix pits with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
