“If the interests of his country were expensive for Bashar, he would have to resign, but he would also have to create the necessary conditions for a new stage of political life,” the king of Jordan, a neighboring country to Syria, told the BBC.
In turn, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoglu expressed regret that Turkey’s mediation efforts, which began earlier this year, have not been successful.
Those in the Middle East who do not live in peace with their people and cannot satisfy their aspirations will lose power, he said, hinting at Syria, a neighboring country towards which Turkey is taking an increasingly tough course.
For its part, the United States welcomes the “expanding consensus against Assad and the actions of the Syrian regime” following the decisions of the League of Arab States and the European Union.
The international community, the United States, the European Union, the League of Arab States and countries such as Turkey are taking an increasingly tough course towards repression in Syria, said Mark Toner, a spokesman for the State Department.
During this time, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of the regime’s armed forces were killed in the Deraa area of southern Syria, according to the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (OSDH).
Two other residents were killed in a shootout and heavy machine gun fire at Jobar in the besieged city of Homs, according to the ONG.
During a press conference, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Muallem said the country was nearing the end of the crisis.
In addition, he reacted sharply to the decision of the League of Arab States to exclude Damascus, which, according to him, is a “dangerous step”.
Syria will not be broken, he added, assuring that this plot against Syria will fail.
Following its decision to exclude Syria, the League of Arab States is currently exploring “a mechanism for the protection of civilians and requires 500 members of the Arab human rights organization, journalists and military observers to come to the country.
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppé also called for UN observers to help protect civilians from the repression of the regime, which he said had fallen into “paranoia.”
A new emergency meeting of the League is scheduled for tomorrow in Rabat to discuss the implementation of the exit plan adopted on 2 November, which includes, inter alia, the withdrawal of the armed forces from the cities where the fighting is taking place and the release of the arrested demonstrators.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov called the decision of the Arab League “incorrect”, while China urged Syria to implement the plan for a way out of the crisis, but refrained from supporting possible sanctions against Damascus.
