Monti demands time from markets and sacrifices from Italians
Italy’s future Prime Minister Mario Monti has asked the markets for some time to form his team and execute a program that will require “sacrifices” to restore creditworthiness lost in the last few months of Berlusconi’s rule.
The former European Commissioner took part in discussions with political parties yesterday ahead of today’s meeting with trade unions and employers.
He will have to form a relatively moderate cabinet composed of technocrats who are not in parliament.
Monti spoke about the importance of a program that involves many casualties, said Francesco Noucara, a spokesman for one of the many small parliamentary groups involved in the discussions following a meeting with a candidate for prime minister.
House Speaker Gianfranco Fini said he would wait to see if Mario Monti would ask parliament to vote confidence before Friday to make sure the new government has enough support.
The meeting will conclude with the submission by Mr. Monti of a limited list of a dozen or so ministers to the head of the country, Giorgio Napolitano.
