His appointment as president was initially endorsed by the markets, but concerns resurfaced, particularly after an unexpected fall in industrial production in the eurozone in September.
The appointed prime minister was to form a team, including, most importantly, technocrats, although he stressed that he would also like to include “politicians.”
The new government will have to operate until 2013, the dates of the next elections, he said.
Speaker of the House of Deputies Gianfranco Fini said the new government would receive a vote of confidence in parliament on Friday.
Mr. Monti guaranteed that once he took office, he would work hard to ensure that Italy would once again become an important actor in Europe.
