Introducing the “Golden Rule” of the Budget to the Constitution
The leadership of the large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to write the budgetary "golden rule" in the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid a possible downgrade by rating agencies of the state credit rating of Austria (triple A).
Social-Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann personally announced the decision at the end of the Council of Ministers meeting, with Austria’s public debt standing at 74.6%, well above the 60% threshold set by the Maastricht Treaty but below the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria’s solvency had fallen by just one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay interest by three thousand million euros more each year, argued Vice Chancellor and Christian Democrat Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Thus, Austria complies with the demand of the Eurozone summit on October 26 in Brussels; the heads of state and government demanded a reduction of budget deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced public accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The ruling by the Austrian government resembles the "German model" because Germany was the first European country to adopt this "rule".
Until 2017, the structural deficit of the state budget should be reduced each year by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP), and from 2017 the structural deficit of the state budget of the federal state in any year should not exceed 0.35% of GDP, and lands, like communes, should represent balanced budgets.
The goal is to force the public debt to fall below the 60% mark set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
