"Japan is struggling to recover" from the March 11 earthquake and tsunami that devastated the Tohoku region (northeast), Mr. Noda said, who fears the yen's rise will kill the fragile embryo of recovery.
The world's third-largest economic power resumed growth in the third quarter -1.5% compared to the previous quarter - for the first time in a year, thanks to the growth of exports and consumption of households affected by the disaster.
But the prime minister feels that the high price of the yen does not reflect Japan’s “fundamental economic performance.”
