Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogma
If there is a topic that cannot be decided after a brief discussion or under the influence of emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election meetings become a reason to reflect on the share and place occupied by nuclear energy.
The dispute will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options have been explored.
France must base its opinion on objective facts and rational data.
With 7,000 million people on the planet now, demographic development will double the need for electricity by 2050, unless the vast majority of the world’s population is deprived of vital elements.
During the same period, it will be necessary to make up for the growing scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue producing electricity continuously, not forgetting the critical need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate imbalances – a topic that has disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these factors.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case in Belgium, which makes its decision dependent on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear power, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are just a few of those who continue their projects decisively.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add one installation to its kit, resuming the construction of the station, which was interrupted after the accident on Three Mile Island.
Although Germany’s renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, reality contradicts this argument.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, increased energy dependence, aggravated by an increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, a jump in carbon dioxide emissions due to the construction of gas and coal plants.
After a few months, all these unpleasant effects will already be felt.
The example of Denmark should be considered.
The European turbine builder, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to intermittent wind; which causes carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices, respectively, to be 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the persistence of our energy policy, our neighbors pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
Since in a globalised economy the price of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and the key to the maintenance of industrial equipment on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear power will lead to a large increase in the cost of electricity, which will illusory beautiful statements about the new industrialization of our country and the protection of purchasing power.
The price that most French people refuse to pay, especially because they do not object to this type of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the country’s energy policy made it possible to create an industry of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect ones.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a pleiade of internationally traded small and medium-sized enterprises and creates many jobs that cannot be relocated to another industry.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would have to sacrifice a large number of these enterprises and lose 6,000 million euros a year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What kind of electrical engineer would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years if its manufacturer was scheduled to close?
To solve the energy equation, one must admit that there are no divine or diabolical sources of energy production.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear energy, maintaining the highest level of security is undoubtedly a vital issue.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centers such as Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is universally recognized, are full of the same obsession with security.
Over the course of 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any consequences for humans or the environment.
In Chernobyl, a reactor device and an unforgivable human error led to tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident occurred as a result of two natural disasters of unprecedented force, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn lessons from this accident, as it has learned from the two previous ones.
The fruit of this step and the cooperation between security authorities, operators and French and German designers, EPR, is a project to counter such phenomena.
Since it is being considered by all energy experts wishing to build a reactor, stopping its construction in Flamanville will be a great gift to competitors Areva and EDF, clearing them the way to gain the leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear energy.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and biased maneuvers to prevail in a dispute that is so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a benefit to the economy?
Immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - overloading police, judicial and administrative services, subject to the policy of figures and the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a "human rights state".
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which got into the news when the Minister of the Interior (Liberación dated May 23) stated that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waiters".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The left and the right agree a lot on this.
The right-wing tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 declared that "900,000 unemployed will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers", and the left by Michel Rocard, who explained in 1990 that France "cannot accept the poor from all over the world".
The only difference is the level of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of invading the territory of the Polish hordes plumber felt both left and right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden on the French economy and on French society.
The difference is only in the level of generosity they will allow to show to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande confined himself to trivialities, saying that “jointly working together will solve our immigration problem.”
This view of immigration as a burden and a problem can give an electoral advantage, but it is very costly economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing the latest data on immigration (Special People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among professionals about the positive impact of migration flows in countries that take it into account in terms of economic growth, wages and wages.
Restricting immigration weakens growth and reduces employment.
Fears of the influence of immigrants are based on the idea that they are able to replace local workers, especially low-skilled ones, provoking lower wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are far more complementary than they are replacing the local workforce by doing jobs for which the local workforce is lacking.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract a local workforce, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training is not tied to job offers.
Positive impact on salaries
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity that exists between locals and immigrants leads to the fact that the arrival of immigrants has a positive effect on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri estimated that a 1% increase in migratory flows leads to a 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
And this is without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to new ideas and economic growth (among the American Nobel Prize winners a large proportion of naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo - all were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also bring net profits to social security systems, giving an average of 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
According to the World Labour Organization, for example, in Germany, an immigrant, arriving at the age of 30, will bring to the state budget a net profit (income minus expenditure) of 150,000 euros on average.
Nicolas Sarkozy at the beginning of his mandate was going to “tooth” to grasp the missing growth points.
The aforementioned teeth, which were used to scare away immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a valuable acquisition; but at the same time fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it experienced the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some believed that in order for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it was enough to organize a vote and make it as direct as possible.
Since the time of Napoleon the "Little" it is known that this comes from the superficiality of thinking.
The universal vote, while a prerequisite for democracy, is not a sufficient prerequisite, and may even become an “instrument of repression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vashro once said.
No, democracy requires many other things - public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of authorities, education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but above all it is a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this respect, the palinody of the truth-and-false Greek referendum will have a double revealing effect, demonstrating both the need for a serious policy change and the unpleasant sense of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality needs to be understood in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front line of the struggle for democracy has now shifted and, according to many, Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We will gain nothing by demanding a series of national referendums organized as needed and in a chaotic manner.
"Carte blanche" for an absolute European monarch or a leap with tied feet into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not dream of a guillotine blade, but of the exercise – jointly, clearly and continuously – of choice and democracy, this time at a pan-European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it is not known how many more will have to be listed, because there is only one crisis - the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is subject to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
Many worry about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but the whole of Europe is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
It is urgent to return the management of the European project to popular sovereignty.
Because only by working together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of everyone’s debt, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
The way out of the crisis will require solutions at the pan-European level, and they cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, without leading us to disaster.
After a long discussion of this proposal, the socialists and Jacques Delors are all now demanding a European economic government.
Let it be.
But to imagine it without stronger economic, political and democratic integration, which has entered into force, is another madness and a new impasse.
We need to start a new phase of European construction.
In order to establish a republic in France, it was necessary to "create" Republicans.
A revolution of interests would not be enough.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a Europe that is united at the economic level.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe at the political level, a real people’s European sovereignty.
To create Europe, let us create Europeans.
