Terrorist Front Spreads from Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about the Islamic Maghreb’s ties to the Boko Haram sect.
The long-anticipated links between the al-Qaeda terrorist group in the Muslim Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria's deputy foreign minister, Abdelkader Messahel, even said that Algerians are now convinced of this.
“The way these two organizations are using and the intelligence reports show that they are actively cooperating,” he said, without going into detail.
Paris seems to have come to similar conclusions.
An investigation into the kidnapping of two French men in Niger in January revealed two links.
Abducted at a restaurant in Niamey by people close to Aqmi, Antoine de Leocourt and Vincent Delory were apparently killed the next day along with several of the kidnappers during an operation carried out by French special forces.
Among the wreckage left after the operation, French and Nigeri investigators found several phone SIM cards belonging to the terrorists.
The Axis of Terror
The analysis of the calls indicated several interlocutors in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two numbers; one pointing to a Nigerian who has long lived in Maidiguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other pointing to a person allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is a step forward, but we certainly need to wait for more reliable evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“It has been known for many years that the sect is receiving financial and ideological support from outside and that it is becoming more and more active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, this support has become increasingly apparent in the actions and statements of Boko Haram and in her methods, which now include the use of suicide bombers and increasingly sophisticated explosive devices of the same type that Aqmi uses.
The international community, led by Washington, is now putting pressure on Abuja to draw attention to the problems Boko Haram is creating.
The fact is that the Nigerian authorities have traditionally viewed this group as a community of enlightened people of no interest.
Rapid success
Founded in 2002 in Maidiguri near a mosque, school, and imam-fundamentalist Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram—which in hausa means “Western education is a sin”—preachs the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the organization achieved rapid success.
It is politicized and demands strict adherence to Sharia, and its activists have begun the fight against the wicked central government.
It is aimed mainly at churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active in carrying out numerous attacks on police stations.
Abuja's reaction, as usual, was uncompromising.
The army blockaded the city and left 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, taken alive, was killed in prison.
Now the sect is radicalized and will go beyond its northern patrimony.
