Nord Stream, a new gateway for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, connecting Western Europe and Russia directly on the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been launched.
It is designed to supply gas to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate the event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between the orchestra’s performance and exquisite snacks, in the opening of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rutte together turned a symbolic valve controlling the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
Under the new pipeline, 27,500 million additional cubic meters of gas will be supplied to Western Europe each year through the first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
The second pipeline should be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas equivalent to the entire consumption of France.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
Nord Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
The two countries will lose some of their power: it will become more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the heaviest moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop at comparing the Nord Stream to the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin with the aim of occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is achieving greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has achieved its understanding of the direct alliance between Russia and wealthy Western countries that consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already running out.
“This pipeline is part of cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that organically binds us,” Fillon said, opening the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel encased in concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields left over from the Second World War.
“A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake weighing the weight of 242 Eiffel Towers, without bursts along its entire length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the Swedish area, but project managers abandoned it because Sweden was not thrilled that a Russian state-owned company would settle permanently off its shores.
“In the event of an accident, we will cut off the flow of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will go into the air.
But that seems unlikely to designers who designed seams designed to leak only once every 100,000 years.
Control over the state of the pipeline will be carried out by an underwater robot, which pulls the ship, for external observation, as well as a device circulating inside the pipeline.
The cigar-shaped apparatus is inserted into the pipe with a diameter of 1 meter and pushed forward by a gas flow.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it gives accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the slightest repair.
The circulation of gas is carried out only at the expense of its pressure.
It is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was tasked with building and operating the pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Then Gazprom leased the company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas is actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 million euros for two pipelines.
GDF Suez will invest around $240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay back their costs, because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The gas pipeline exits from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy shore planted with coniferous trees.
The valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit terminal.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 6 million.
Moleskine brand notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company fifteen years ago, will bring back the taste of writing.
He has the scent of adventure, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easy to recognize by the rectangular black cover, by the elastic, by the yellowish-white pages, as if yellowed with time.
The Moleskine notebook, however, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
Italian company Modo Modo, located in Milan, decided to launch designer notebooks.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant to the company, took responsibility for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique, moleskin - lacquered cotton fabric, used, for example, for covering benches.
This type of notebook is said to be highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine aligned with today’s taste an old and forgotten thing that was iconic for avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the managing brand at Modo Modo.
Success has arrived.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales grew by 25% to reach 12.7 million units.
We were far from producing the first few years, when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish the profile of a typical buyer, because the notebook equally attracts a businessman, a student and a person of the free profession.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, have broad views and are educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in Fnac bookstores, shops in the centers of small towns and has been able to gain wide fame.
“We followed the spirit of the time and this new need for a letter, despite the advent of email,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This distinctive cultural trait accompanies the development of Moleskine; recently the brand organized an exhibition “Around the Road”, where architects and artists demonstrated their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched covers with a leopard pattern on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its successes and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags. The brand includes all kinds of support.
In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which wrote a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for disabled people begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate among persons with disabilities is still twice the average, namely 19 per cent versus 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Discouraged?
“No,” said Eric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for disabled people.
“In 15 years, significant progress has been made.”
"At that time, the share of unemployed was not 2 times, but 3 times more."
“But there is still a lot of work ahead.”
There are many barriers to employment for people with disabilities.
Among them are more elderly: 37% older than 50 years (17% on average).
Rather, they have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for the disabled versus 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to get back to work and that are at the heart of the problem,” says Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association commissioned by Cité found that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and "imagined solid people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally impaired."
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6% disabled workers set out in a law passed in 1987.
The latest known figures for 2008 are 2.6%.
“Today we’re at about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that don’t comply with the law.
Evidence: The number of “taxable” organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law that raised the tax put a lot of pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects an increase in awareness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with a number of employees from 20 to 49 have employees with disabilities, compared to 82% of organizations with a number of employees from 100 to 199.
